\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The free-falling smart-dust model offers a promising way of thinking about
 the physical properties of spacetime.
 In most ways, it is identical to the 120 year-old concept of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

observers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 located in spacetime.
 What's new is that it abstracts the core properties of what observers can
 actually do: they can measure time, they can send and receive messages,
 and they can perform computations.
 They can be shrunk to microscopic dimensions, thus avoiding ambiguities
 associated with spatially-extended objects (such as rulers, which are elastic
 at the macro level, and are composed of quantum objects at the micro level.)
 The smart dust is assumed to be entirely classical (non-quantum).
 Since the smart dust can perform computations, it can be used to simulate
 Huygens sums and/or other quantum concepts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first attempt at working with smart dust, in Chapter Three, falters
 on the use of Schwarzschild coordinates.
 The second attempt, in Chapter Five, does better, by selecting the Gullstrand–P
ainlevé chart.
 It still falters, for two reasons.
 First, by working in spherical coordinates, sphere symmetry is actually
 hidden.
 This is because the transformations between coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 , to another location 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, while conceptually simple, are horrible tangled in practice.
 Euler angles are nasty.
 Pauli matrices (which are rectilinear) are nice.
 The second mistake is that of working in coordinate space directly, instead
 of working with vierbeins (frame fields).
 This second mistake results in the entanglement of coordinate transformation
 effects with laboratory frame measurements.
 Fierbeins disentangle global coordinate choices from local laboratory measureme
nts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

river model of black holes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


