\begin_layout Subsection
Metric and frame fields, semi-index-free
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The starting point is the Cartesian form of the Gullstrand–Painlevé metric,
 given in Appendix D.
 Repeating this, the metric is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{g}= & \eta_{\mu\nu}\left(dx^{\mu}+\beta^{\mu}dx^{0}\right)\otimes\left(dx^{\nu}+\beta^{\nu}dx^{0}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is the radial 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

river velocity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\beta^{0} & =0\\
\beta^{i} & =\beta\left(r\right)\frac{x^{i}}{r}\quad\mbox{for }i=1,2,3
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The sign are such that this metric is consistent with the sphere-coordinate
 metric, given earlier.
 Despite all the plus signs above, the river velocity is infalling.
 This follows from the metric signature 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\mu\nu}=\left(+---\right)$
\end_inset

, which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}=-\beta^{i}$
\end_inset

 and the lower index reminds that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a vector in the tangent space.
 Positive vectors point outwards; thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 with these conventions points inwards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For Gullstrand–Painlevé, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\left(r\right)=\sqrt{\frac{2m}{r}}
\]

\end_inset

although, in general, slightly more general 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

 are allowed, e.g.
 for Reissner–Nordström, and even further still, if the Francis–Kosowsky
 technique is followed (see the Appendix.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The metric is factored into flat tetrad frame fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{g}_{\mu}=\partial_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{\mu\nu}=\mathbf{g}_{\mu}\cdot\mathbf{g}_{\nu}=\mathbf{g}_{\mu}^{a}\mathbf{g}_{\nu}^{b}\eta_{ab}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{ab}=\gamma_{a}\cdot\gamma_{b}=\gamma_{a}^{\mu}\gamma_{b}^{\nu}g_{\mu\nu}
\]

\end_inset

Hamilton&Lisle
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hamilton2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue that, for Gullstrand–Painlevé in Cartesian form, one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\gamma_{0} & =\mathbf{g}_{0}-\beta^{i}\mathbf{g}_{i}\\
\gamma_{i} & =\mathbf{g}_{i}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3$
\end_inset

.
 Note the sign is reversed from Hamilton&Lisle; this is obtained below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

magic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is that these eqns have the form of a Galilean transformation, which shifts
 the time axis by a velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}$
\end_inset

 along the direction of motion, but leaves the time component (of the time
 axis) itself unchanged.
 The spatial axes are unchanged.
 
\end_layout

