 River Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{a}$
\end_inset

 is the velocity of the particle with respect to the co-moving lab frame.
 It is generally understood that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lab frame
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a stand-in for the coordinates of the tangent plane 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 for point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

 in the spacetime manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 This is all fine and well, except that this carries the mental baggage
 of a physical laboratory with walls and a workbench made of atoms.
 These are elastic, and subject to deformation by tidal stress.
 Worse, in a real laboratory, particles at different ends of the room fall
 in different directions.
 The perfectly-rigid tangent plane does not allow such comparisons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To overcome this conceptual difficulty, Hamilton&Lisle propose the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

River Model of Spacetime
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Here, the physical interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{a}$
\end_inset

 is that it is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

4-velocity of the particle, relative to the inflowing river of space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This allows Hamilton&Lisle to make the following additional statements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Proper time is a property of the particle (the geodesic) and not of the
 river (spacetime).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Particles in the river move from one part of the river to another according
 to the rules of special relativity.
 That is, when a particle is displaced in a direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

, it is Lorentz-boosted by some amount, depending on the river location.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a rotating background (Kerr solution), displacements have both a boost
 and a rotation (six degrees of freedom, an anti-symmetric tensor).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The river itself flows in a Galilean fashion, through a flat Galilean background.
 I don't understand this comment.
 Galilean transforms are affine transformations, having the form 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to x^{\prime}=x+vt$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $vt$
\end_inset

 the affine displacement.
 The relation between 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{a}$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{g}_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 does not have this form.
 I don't see what the flow is.
 I don't see what's Galilean.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It certainly is the case that the frame field 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{a}\in T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

 is just a linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{a}^{\;\mu}$
\end_inset

 of the coordinate tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

