\begin_layout Subsection
River Model vs.
 Smart Dust
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The practical question behind all this is how to understand what is happening
 in a free-falling inertial laboratory frame.
 There are multiple issues that need to be resolved.
 Primary is how to measure space-like distances.
 Physical (e.g.
 wooden, steel) meter-sticks present a problem: they experience tidal forces
 that must be resisted by atomic bonds.
 This requires treatment of the elasticity of the ruler.
 The two ends of the ruler are not in free-fall: the atoms in between push
 away.
 There's also a different problem: what are the locations (world-lines)
 of the atoms in the ruler? That is, the atoms are located with respect
 to what coordinate frame? The molecular bonds between atoms are generally
 analyzed for a fixed space-like surface, but what is that surface? What
 is meant by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

simultaneity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

? How do we disentangle the effect of spacetime itself from the compressive
 forces of tidal variation? The River Model appears to provide an intuitive
 way of grappling with these questions.
 But I'm not sure its enough, so lets keep going.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To avoid questions about the behavior of elastic materials, one can instead
 attempt to measure distances using light rays.
 This simplifies matters dramatically.
 Some postulates:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Clocks can be made arbitrarily small, and so there is no ambiguity as to
 where they are, when they measure time.
 If they are in free-fall, they measure proper time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Distances can be measured by bouncing light rays off a mirror, and measuring
 round-trip travel time.
 This requires two subsidiary assumptions, as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Pulses of light can be made arbitrarily short, so that there is no ambiguity
 as to the pulse location.
 They can be made point-like.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mirrors can be made arbitrarily small, so that there is no ambiguity as
 to the location of a mirror.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final postulate is to replace the mirror by a transceiver, so that the
 mirror becomes an active agent, instead of passively reflecting.
 That is, upon receipt of a light signal, it is instantaneously decoded,
 stamped with new information about the mirror, and then returned to sender.
 If the needed computations cannot be done instantaneously, then the reply
 message can still contain local timestamps of receipt and re-transmission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this way, the River Model is replaced by a Smart Dust Model: a collection
 of free-falling clocks, infinitesimal in size, able to receive and transmit
 complex messages in infinitesimal packets.
 The info packets can travel either along null geodesics (as light pulses),
 or as massive bullets, along time-like geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Smart Dust Model avoids having to struggle with the idea that clocks
 in different parts of the laboratory run at different rates, and with having
 to triangulate mirror locations.
 It avoids having to build and analyze the behavior of interferometers.
 Fully smart dust enables for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smart classical interferometers
