\begin_layout Subsection
Parallel transport in Coordinate Frames
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transport of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 along a direction 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is famously given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dp^{\mu}}{d\tau}+\Gamma_{\;\rho\nu}^{\mu}u^{\rho}p^{\nu}=0
\]

\end_inset

This is a differential equation; thus 
\begin_inset Formula $dp^{\mu}/dt=\dot{p}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is the instantaneous rate of change.
 By construction (by definition?) one has that the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{\;\nu}^{\mu}=\Gamma_{\;\rho\nu}^{\mu}u^{\rho}
\]

\end_inset

is always an element in the Lie algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{so}\left(1,3\right)$
\end_inset

 for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\rho}$
\end_inset

.
 This is necessarily the case: the structure group of general relativity
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{so}\left(1,3\right)$
\end_inset

 cause we made it that way.
 Of course, any element 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\;\nu}^{\mu}\in\mathfrak{so}\left(1,3\right)$
\end_inset

 is an infinitissimal Lorentz transform (again, by definition) and so the
 infinitessimal variation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p^{0} & \to p^{0}+\delta p^{0}=p^{0}+\lambda_{\;\nu}^{0}p^{\nu}\delta\tau\\
p^{i} & \to p^{i}+\delta p^{i}=p^{i}+\lambda_{\;\nu}^{i}p^{\nu}\delta\tau
\end{align*}

\end_inset

will necessarily look like an infinitessimal Lorentz boost+rotation.
\end_layout

