\begin_layout Subsection
Vectors in the coordinate and tetrad frames
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

, a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}\in T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 can be expressed either in terms of the coordinate tangent vector basis
 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

, or in the orthonormal frame field basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{a}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

.
 Either basis is equally valid.
 Greek and roman indexes distinguish between the two.
 Thus, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 is written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{p}=p^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}=p^{\mu}\mathbf{g}_{\mu}=p^{a}\gamma_{a}
\]

\end_inset

Given the Gullstrand–Painlevé chart, the two are related as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p^{a}=\delta_{\mu}^{a}p^{\mu}+\beta^{a}p^{0}
\]

\end_inset

This generalizes the result for velocity, given earlier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equations of Motion in the Tetrad Frame
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
