\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{a}$
\end_inset

 be a free-falling observer, in the tetrad frame.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{a}$
\end_inset

 be a tangent vector, freefalling with the observer.
 Hamilton claims the equations of motion in the tetrad frame are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dp^{a}}{d\tau}+\Gamma_{\;bc}^{a}p^{b}u^{c}=0
\]

\end_inset

This looks entirely reasonable, we take it as gospel.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Christoffel symbols (copied, guessing sign) are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Gamma_{0j}^{i} & =-\frac{\partial\beta^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}\\
\Gamma_{ij}^{0} & =\frac{\partial\beta^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}\quad\mbox{for }i,j=1,2,3
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This seems correct; the minus signs are needed here to make the later sections,
 below, work out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Relative Motion in the Tetrad Frame
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $c:\mathbb{R}\to M$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 is parameterized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and gives a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=c\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 lying in the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 It's parameterized to be of unit speed, so that at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 it has an instantaneous velocity given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}c\left(\tau\right)=\dot{c}\left(\tau\right)=v^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}=u^{a}\gamma_{a}\in T_{\xi}M
\]

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\mu}v_{\mu}=u^{a}u_{a}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The curve 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is assumed to describe the motion of an observer (a particle of smart dust),
 perhaps free-falling, and perhaps not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fixing the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{c}\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 at fixed proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, the parallel transport eqn is then a mapping from any arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{a}\in T_{\xi}M$
\end_inset

 to another 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{p}^{a}\in T_{\xi}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dp^{a}}{d\tau}=\dot{p}^{a}=-\Gamma_{\;bc}^{a}p^{b}u^{c}
\]

\end_inset

This can be treated as a differential equation, which, when integrated,
 gives the motion of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{a}\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 along the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

, or, more generally, the motion of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\xi}M$
\end_inset

 as it is carried along the curve.
 As noted earlier, the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\;b}^{a}=\Gamma_{\;bc}^{a}u^{c}$
\end_inset

 is an infinitessimal Lorentz transform; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\;b}^{a}\in\mathfrak{so}\left(1,3\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plugging through for the Christoffel symbols, the equations of motion are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dp^{0}}{d\tau} & =-\frac{\partial\beta_{i}}{\partial x^{j}}p^{i}u^{j}\\
\frac{dp^{i}}{d\tau} & =\frac{\partial\beta^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}p^{0}u^{j}\quad\mbox{for }i,j=1,2,3
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}=-\beta^{i}$
\end_inset

 for our signature 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(+---\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This passes the sniff test.
 If the curve is radially infalling, then 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{j}=0$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{0}=1$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $dp^{0}/d\tau=dp^{i}/d\tau=0$
\end_inset

 and vectors are transported without change.
 All is well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But what about the case of general 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{a}?$
\end_inset

 The equations have the structure of a Lorentz boost.
 This is made painfully clear yet again by fixing the observer velocity
 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{a}$
\end_inset

 and defining a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{a}$
\end_inset

 (w for 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

water
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
w^{0} & =0\\
w^{i} & =\frac{\partial\beta^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}u^{j}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The equations of motion simplify to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dp^{0}}{d\tau} & =-w_{i}p^{i}\\
\frac{dp^{i}}{d\tau} & =w^{i}p^{0}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This has exactly the algebraic structure of an infinitessimal Lorentz boost,
 after being careful to note the sign, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=-w^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 In matrix form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{p}^{a}=\lambda_{\;b}^{a}p^{b}
\]

\end_inset

or written in component form,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
\dot{p}^{0}\\
\dot{p}^{1}\\
\dot{p}^{2}\\
\dot{p}^{3}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & w^{1} & w^{2} & w^{3}\\
w^{1} & 0 & 0 & 0\\
w^{2} & 0 & 0 & 0\\
w^{3} & 0 & 0 & 0
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
p^{0}\\
p^{1}\\
p^{2}\\
p^{3}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

with the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 behaving properly under the transpose, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{T}=\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And yet, its odd.
 In normal flat Minkowski space, an observer travelling with velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{a}$
\end_inset

 would see a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{a}$
\end_inset

 transformed exactly as above, but with 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{a}$
\end_inset

 in place of 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, in flat space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\mu\nu}^{0}=-\Gamma_{0\nu}^{\mu}=\delta_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\;\nu}^{\mu}=-\delta_{0}^{\mu}u_{\nu}+u^{\mu}\delta_{\nu}^{0}$
\end_inset

 (extra minus sign because, again, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\nu}=-u^{\nu}$
\end_inset

) and so the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{a}$
\end_inset

 provides the infinitessimal Lorentz transform.
 Here, it is twisted; instead, 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{a}=M_{\;b}^{a}u^{b}\ne u^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 So yes, the tetrad frame defines a free-falling virtual lab, but it is
 screwy.
 Yes, relative motion is given by a boost; but that boost is not the one
 of flat space.
 It's messed up.
 Everthing is still special relativity, but its a special kind of special
 relativity.
 That's because the lab frame is falling through curved space.
\end_layout

