\begin_layout Subsection
Explicit Tetrad expressions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the general case, we need explicit expressions.
 These are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial\beta^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}= & \frac{\partial}{\partial x^{j}}\beta\left(r\right)\frac{x^{i}}{r}\\
= & -\frac{1}{2}\frac{x^{i}}{r}\frac{\beta}{r}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{j}}r+\beta\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{j}}\frac{x^{i}}{r}\\
= & -\beta\frac{x^{i}x^{k}\delta_{jk}}{2r^{3}}+\beta\left(\frac{\delta_{j}^{i}}{r}-\frac{x^{i}x^{k}\delta_{jk}}{r^{3}}\right)\\
= & \beta\frac{2r^{2}\delta_{j}^{i}-3x^{i}x^{k}\delta_{jk}}{2r^{3}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{jk}$
\end_inset

 is used to drop the index, so as to avoid confusion about signs.
 That is, use 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\sqrt{x^{i}x^{j}\delta_{ij}}$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting expression looks typical for sphere-symmetrical central-force
 Cartesian coords.
 Not particularly enlightening.
 In particular, the angular momentum should be a constant of motion, but
 that is certainly not apparent in this expression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because there is sphere symmtery, we can take, without loss of generality,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{1}=r,\;x^{2}=x^{3}=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{i}=r\delta_{1}^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging through, this gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\beta^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}=\frac{\beta}{r}\left(\delta_{j}^{i}-\frac{3}{2}\delta_{1}^{i}\delta_{j}^{1}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which is purely diagonal, and distinguishes the radial axis from the two
 transverse ones.
 Remarkably, there is a sign change.
 Not sure what that means.
 In matrix form,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\beta^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}=M_{\;j}^{i}=\frac{\beta}{r}\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
-\frac{1}{2} & 0 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Recalling that 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{0}=0,$
\end_inset

the rest of the boost is 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{i}=M_{\;j}^{i}u^{j}$
\end_inset

 or, in matrix form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w^{i}=\frac{\beta}{r}\left[\begin{array}{c}
-u^{1}/2\\
u^{2}\\
u^{3}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

The equations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dp^{0}}{d\tau} & =-w_{i}p^{i}\\
\frac{dp^{i}}{d\tau} & =w^{i}p^{0}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

can be written in matrix form as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dp^{a}}{d\tau}=\lambda_{\;b}^{a}p^{b}
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{\;b}^{a}=\frac{\beta}{r}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & -u^{1}/2 & u^{2} & u^{3}\\
-u^{1}/2 & 0 & 0 & 0\\
u^{2} & 0 & 0 & 0\\
u^{3} & 0 & 0 & 0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

It's a generator of an infinitessimal boost.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{1}$
\end_inset

 direction is the infalling direction; the 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{3}$
\end_inset

 directions are flat-space directions.
 Recall, for flat space, we'd have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\lambda_{\mbox{flat}}=\kappa=K_{i}u^{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{i}$
\end_inset

 the conventiona generators of boosts.
 That is, in flat space, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa_{\;b}^{a}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & u^{1} & u^{2} & u^{3}\\
u^{1} & 0 & 0 & 0\\
u^{2} & 0 & 0 & 0\\
u^{3} & 0 & 0 & 0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and so indeed the 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{3}$
\end_inset

 components are flat (except that they are rescaled by 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta/r$
\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{1}$
\end_inset

 direction is both sign-reversed, and cut in half.
 I'm not quite sure how to explain this.
 I guess the minus sign is the result of infalling.
\end_layout

